e from Anglo-Norman French <i>del isle</i> ‘from the island’ (from Latin <i>de insula</i>), denoting someone who lived on an island or who came from a place in France named Ile, Isle, or L'Isle. The surname may also in some cases be from Lille (Nord). Compare   Lisle   and   Iles  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyles","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lyle   1."]},{"name":"Lisle","meanings":["English (Northumberland, Durham, and Yorkshire): variant of   Lyle   and a cognate of 2 below.","French: habitational name from L'Isle or Lisle, names of several places in various parts of France, named with Old French <i>isle</i> ‘island’ (from Latin <i>insula</i>). Compare   Delisle  ."]}]},{"name":"Aaron","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the brother of Moses, who was appointed by God to be Moses' spokesman and became the first High Priest of the Israelites (Exodus 4:14–16, 7:1–2). It is of uncertain origin and meaning: most probably, like   Moses  , of Egyptian rather than Hebrew origin. The traditional derivation from Hebrew <i>har-on</i> ‘mountain of strength’ is no more than a folk etymology. The name has been in regular use from time immemorial as a Jewish name and was taken up by the Nonconformists as a Christian name in the 16th century. Since the late 1990s it has been widely popular."],"variants":[{"name":"Arun","meanings":["‘reddish-brown’, the colour of dawn, gold, and rubies, and personification of the dawn, the charioteer of the sun."]},{"name":"Arron","meanings":["Variant of either   Aaron   or   Arran ."]},{"name":"Aron","meanings":["Simplified form of   Aaron ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Aaron Lyle was born in 1352, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Lyle, was 24 and his mother, Margaret de Vaux, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Lady Catherine Kilmarnock Of Kilmamock